ence and impact of competing courts, Howard discovers that fairness before the law may be a laudable goal, but the appointment process ensures that tax policy and tax enforcement rulings by the courts reflect the perspectives of the dominant political coalition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aJustice, Administration ofzUnited States. 0aTax collectionzUnited States. 0aTax courtszUnited States. 0aTax protests and appealszUnited States. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 4aPublic Policy : Public Policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / Judicial Branch.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143842890140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438428901423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438428901/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles